American troops, and 12 years of UN Weapons Inspectors, have yet to produce any evidence of the existence of such materiel.<br>
<br>
North Korea announced today that it *has* nuclear weapons.  For several months before today's news, NK has threatened to fire up a nuclear power plant.  Yet the Bush administration doesn't seem to care about an *actual* rogue nation.  Instead, they chase at the old bugbears that they placed into power, and throw up a smokescreen to confuse the American public.  No &quot;weapons of mass destruction&quot; have yet been found in Iraq.  They do not exist.  And yet, halfway across the world, we have a Stalin-loving dictator that openly defies international laws, runs a country that can't even provide food and electricity to its own people, and makes public annoucements about how little it cares about the world's opinion.  But this all is OK with the Government Appointed by Florida?  I'm very curious how you conservatives try to justify this. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jarkellraven>JarkellRaven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blessed of Bristlebane</span><br>  Posts: 2388<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/26/03 5:15:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Weapons of Mass Destruction.</span><hr size=1> Well, I'm obviously not conservative.<br>
<br>
However, to put it simply, Iraq did not pose a serious danger.  North Korea does.  War with North Korea could be dangerous for a variety of reasons, and could lead to either a brutally long war or a brutally short one, involving nuclear missiles.  We're not at war with North Korea because we can't be.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, this teaches exactly the lesson we didn't want to teach, namely that to avoid the teranny of the United States, one must defend one's nation with Weapons of Mass Destruction, and have the delievery systems to use them.  Thus, we encourage WMDs as well as make ourselves the big bad guy to be defended against.<br>
<br>
Of course this was part of the reason I was against the Iraqi war, the other being that increased anger towards the United States would lead to a serious upswing in terrorism.  We'll see if I'm right in that fear.  I hope I am not.<br>
<br>
Jarkell Ravensteel <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jaranna>Jaranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 490<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/26/03 5:27:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Weapons of Mass Destruction.</span><hr size=1> I don't try to justify it.<br>
<br>
Let's say we find absolutely no WMD in Iraq.  None.  Nada.  Was the conflict still worth it?  Damn right it was.  The Iraqi people are now free of a dictator who was in power way too long.  We'll see how they follow it up with a new government.<br>
<br>
But I believe Iraq had WMDs before the war.  They may be buried.  They might have been evacuated to another country.  Or they might not have had any after all.  Anything is possible.  But I do believe Iraq had them, and, as such, the cease-fire of 1991 was null and void.<br>
<br>
So, why didn't we go for North Korea, too?  Simple.  Fight one conflict at a time.  It was my understanding that North Korea was still talking earnestly with us about the situation.<br>
<br>
But you tell me--is there a U.N. resolution that states that North Korea cannot have any WMD?  It's not a smartass question.  I really don't know. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elsbetsquishytoes>elsbet squishytoes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Grey</span><br>  Posts: 797<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/26/03 5:33:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Weapons of Mass Destruction.</span><hr size=1> We're on the same page, Jark.  I'm just trying to figure out the Republicans' side of the argument, because, to me, it holds absolutely no value.  We invaded Iraq, because, erm, it had WMD that we, with our very impressive array of technology and years of surveillance, are not able to produce?  We can pinpoint the location of a supposed leader of Al-Qaeda in a truck in Yemen, yet we can't find the location of Iraq's Top Secret A-Bomb Factory, where we've been a constant presence for over a decade?<br>
<br>
I know we are scared to piss of North Korea, because a fight with China would not be fun for anyone, but I'm just questioning the basic logic behind invading Iraq and not NK.  What is it that Rush Limbaugh and Bill O'Reilly say that makes you conservatives agree so blindly with the limp-minded propaganda spewed forth from the White House these days? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gyreredbranch>Gyre Redbranch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 177<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/26/03 8:01:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Weapons of Mass Destruction.</span><hr size=1> This is simple, actually:<br>
