The Electoral College system was put in place so that a candidate could spend time campaigning only in a few key places in order to win the popular election, and thus the Presidency.  As you can see by the famous red and blue &quot;No Mandate?&quot; map, Al Gore won a few key locations in the popular election, but he still didn't have a majority of the votes.  He was at 49%, but a few percentage points higher than Bush.<br>
